{"parse":{"title":"Ruskin Pottery","pageid":374952,"revid":858346112,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ruskinpottery.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Ruskinpottery.jpg/220px-Ruskinpottery.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"172\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Ruskinpottery.jpg/330px-Ruskinpottery.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Ruskinpottery.jpg/440px-Ruskinpottery.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2872\" data-file-height=\"2244\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ruskinpottery.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A selection of wares from the Ruskin Pottery in 'high fired' reduction glazes</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ruskinplaques.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0a/Ruskinplaques.jpg/220px-Ruskinplaques.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"167\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0a/Ruskinplaques.jpg/330px-Ruskinplaques.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0a/Ruskinplaques.jpg/440px-Ruskinplaques.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1896\" data-file-height=\"1440\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ruskinplaques.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A selection of the ceramic plaques made by the Ruskin Pottery</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ruskinsouffle.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/ab/Ruskinsouffle.jpg/220px-Ruskinsouffle.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"252\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/ab/Ruskinsouffle.jpg/330px-Ruskinsouffle.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/ab/Ruskinsouffle.jpg/440px-Ruskinsouffle.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1660\" data-file-height=\"1904\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ruskinsouffle.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A group of Ruskin Pottery souffl\u00e9, 1905-1913</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>Ruskin Pottery</b> was an English pottery studio founded in 1898 by <a href=\"/wiki/Edward_R._Taylor\" title=\"Edward R. Taylor\">Edward R. Taylor</a>, the first Principal of both the <a href=\"/wiki/Lincoln_School_of_Art\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lincoln School of Art\">Lincoln School of Art</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Birmingham_School_of_Art\" title=\"Birmingham School of Art\">Birmingham School of Art</a>, to be run by his son, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=William_Howson_Taylor&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"William Howson Taylor (page does not exist)\">William Howson Taylor</a>, formerly a student there. It was named after the artist, writer and social thinker  <a href=\"/wiki/John_Ruskin\" title=\"John Ruskin\">John Ruskin</a>, as the Taylors agreed with, and followed the tenets of Ruskin.  The pottery was situated at 173-174 Oldbury Road, <a href=\"/wiki/Smethwick\" title=\"Smethwick\">Smethwick</a>, then in Staffordshire (now part of <a href=\"/wiki/Sandwell\" title=\"Sandwell\">Sandwell</a>, in the <a href=\"/wiki/West_Midlands_(county)\" title=\"West Midlands (county)\">West Midlands</a> county).\n</p><p>The pottery produced was notable for the innovative glazes used on a range of brightly coloured pots, vases, buttons, bowls, tea services and jewellery. The glazes devised by <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=William_Howson_Taylor&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"William Howson Taylor (page does not exist)\">William Howson Taylor</a> included misty souffl\u00e9 glazes, ice crystal effect glazes - 'crystalline', lustre glazes resembling metallic finishes, and the most highly regarded of all, \u201csang de boeuf\u201d and Flambe glazes which produced a blood red effect.   The 'sang de boeuf' glazes were created using reduction of copper and iron oxides at high temperature. This was a difficult technique, first developed in China in the 13th century and reinvented by several art potters in Europe in the late 19th century. William Howson Taylor was one of the principal exponents of 'high fired' techniques, producing a range of colours and unique 'fissured' glaze effects.\n</p><p>Having exhibited at home and at international fine art exhibitions, the award of a \"grand prize\" in 1904 at the <a href=\"/wiki/Louisiana_Purchase_Exposition\" title=\"Louisiana Purchase Exposition\">St Louis International Exhibition</a>, gave them the recognition they needed. Further awards were gained at other international exhibitions, including <a href=\"/wiki/Milan_International_(1906)\" title=\"Milan International (1906)\">Milan 1906</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/International_Exhibition_(1906)\" title=\"International Exhibition (1906)\">Christchurch, New Zealand, 1907</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/Franco-British_Exhibition_(1908)\" title=\"Franco-British Exhibition (1908)\">London 1908</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/Brussels_International_1910\" title=\"Brussels International 1910\">Brussels 1910</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/Turin_International\" title=\"Turin International\">Turin 1911</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/Exposition_universelle_et_internationale_(1913)\" title=\"Exposition universelle et internationale (1913)\">Ghent 1913</a>.\n</p><p>When the studio closed in 1935 the formulae for the glazes and all the pottery documentation were deliberately destroyed, so that the unique Ruskin products could never be replicated. \n</p><p>A large collection of Ruskin Pottery is on public display at <a href=\"/wiki/Wednesbury_Museum_and_Art_Gallery\" title=\"Wednesbury Museum and Art Gallery\">Wednesbury Museum and Art Gallery</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Wednesbury\" title=\"Wednesbury\">Wednesbury</a>, about 3.5 miles (5.6&#160;km) north of the factory. The collection is owned by Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council and is managed by Sandwell Museum Service.\n</p><p>The site of the factory is now an industrial estate, <i>\"Ruskin Place\"</i>. A <a href=\"/wiki/Blue_plaque\" title=\"Blue plaque\">blue plaque</a> marking the site, erected by the Smethwick Local History Society, was subsequently stolen.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ruskin_Pottery&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Garland, A., 'Art and the Drama', pp. 110-119, in <i>Lincoln, Nineteen Hundred &amp; Thirty Six', National Association of Head Teachers 1936 Conference, 1936, p. 115</i></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Smethwick Local History Society newsletter</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li><i>The Pottery of Edward Richard Taylor and William Howson Taylor, 1898-1935</i> - <a href=\"/wiki/Paul_Atterbury\" title=\"Paul Atterbury\">Paul Atterbury</a> and John Henson, Baxendale Press, 1993, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-9520933-0-8\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-9520933-0-8\">0-9520933-0-8</a></li></ul>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span id=\"coordinates\"><a href=\"/wiki/Geographic_coordinate_system\" title=\"Geographic coordinate system\">Coordinates</a>: <span class=\"plainlinks nourlexpansion\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Ruskin_Pottery&amp;params=52.50257_N_1.9928_W_region:GB_type:landmark\"><span class=\"geo-nondefault\"><span class=\"geo-dms\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\"><span class=\"latitude\">52\u00b030\u203209\u2033N</span> <span class=\"longitude\">1\u00b059\u203234\u2033W</span></span></span><span class=\"geo-multi-punct\">&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;</span><span class=\"geo-default\"><span class=\"geo-dec\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\">52.50257\u00b0N 1.99280\u00b0W</span><span style=\"display:none\">&#xfeff; / <span class=\"geo\">52.50257; -1.99280</span></span></span></a></span></span></span>\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cardium_pottery_example.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Cardium_pottery_example.png/25px-Cardium_pottery_example.png\" width=\"25\" height=\"20\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Cardium_pottery_example.png/38px-Cardium_pottery_example.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Cardium_pottery_example.png/50px-Cardium_pottery_example.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"555\" data-file-height=\"443\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Ceramics_(art)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ceramics (art)\">ceramic art</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Design\" title=\"Design\">design</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia 